text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeArticle:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingComment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!PracticeCategory]]%0a%0a!That multilingual voice in your head… %0a%0a:Author: roochis%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0a Can multilingual people think in multiple languages? If so, how? %0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aI grew up learning a language that isn't English, but I can't think in that language. When my father immigrated to the US, he said that he was able to better learn English by forcing himself to think in it. He says that today he thinks in both English and Gujarati (his primary language), and I wonder what types of thoughts/emotions are associated with each language. I find it hard to believe that he switches back and forth completely randomly. There must be some rhyme and reason to it. I know when bilingual people speak to each other they often switch back and forth seamlessly because (I'm assuming) some ideas can be better expressed in one language as opposed to another. Thinking is more automatic than verbally communicating, so I wonder how that works.  %0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210206-010029-266010#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Thinking in multiple languages while learning %0a-> - VikramM%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aIn my personal experience learning a second language for several years, I remember at one time dealing with the new language by translating to English, formulating a response in English, and finally translating back to the other language and then speaking or writing. After a certain point (I'm not exactly sure exactly when), I remember just being able to think in the second language in class/whenever it was used around me and no longer doing the back and forth translation. It definitely made speaking/conversation much easier and faster. Something interesting is that the transition happened right around when the classes I was taking started focusing more on reading/listening to real media in that language rather than concentrating on more grammatical/structure oriented aspects. More on the topic of your question, I think that the language one thinks in can be dependent on what is being spoken around them. %0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210206-010029-266010#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a#foxbegin 210206-005039-958360#%0a(:div1 class=messagehead:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a[-05.02.2021 - 16:50-] &nbsp; %0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c%0a{[foxdelrange button 210206-005039-958360 {$FullName} ]}%0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:if1end:)%0a!!!!!lauray%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0a'''I think they can'''%0a>>messageitem%3c%3c%0aI grew up learning Chinese and English at pretty much the same time and though I generally find myself thinking in English, I feel like there have been times when I just think in Chinese. One odd example is that when I was learning Spanish I would find myself thinking in Chinese a lot. I've even accidentally spoken Chinese in Spanish Class because of this. I think this was probably because my mind connected a different language automatically to the other language that I knew which was Chinese. I feel like I think in Chinese when I'm consuming some sort of foreign show or trying to express myself in a way that English can't. Also when I'm speaking purely in Chinese sometimes I feel like I also think in Chinese. %0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210206-005039-958360#%0a#foxbegin 210204-215145-357140#%0a(:div1 class=messagehead:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a[-04.02.2021 - 13:51-] &nbsp; %0a>>%3c%3c%0a!!!!!rachelc%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0a'''I've wondered the same thing'''%0a>>messageitem%3c%3c%0aI've also wondered this! I would assume that context matters, for instance if someone speaks say English at work and Spanish at home if they also tend to think in English at work and Spanish at home, but even if this is true in general I'm sure there would be exceptions and I'm curious how those would work. %0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210204-215145-357140#%0a%0a%0a%0a(:Section: :)%0a(:Category: PracticeCategory:)
