diff:1612573229:1612572639:=45,53c45%0a%3c #foxbegin 210206-010029-266010#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!Thinking in multiple languages while learning %0a%3c -> - VikramM%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c In my personal experience learning a second language for several years, I remember at one time dealing with the new language by translating to English, formulating a response in English, and finally translating back to the other language and then speaking or writing. After a certain point (I'm not exactly sure exactly when), I remember just being able to think in the second language in class/whenever it was used around me and no longer doing the back and forth translation. It definitely made speaking/conversation much easier and faster. Something interesting is that the transition happened right around when the classes I was taking started focusing more on reading/listening to real media in that language rather than concentrating on more grammatical/structure oriented aspects. More on the topic of your question, I think that the language one thinks in can be dependent on what is being spoken around them. %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 210206-010029-266010#%0a---%0a> %0a
